House Selling Prices

The goal of this assignment was to create a model that accurately predicts house selling prices. To start my analysis I ran an lm for each variable with SalePrice and made note of the highest \(R^2\)s (.3 and up). I summed each of those all together in a model and got a pretty high \(R^2\) of around .83.

I will now walk through the rest of the steps I took to get my lm.

Box-Cox

Box-Cox

boxCox(lm)

I decided to run a Box-Cox on my model to see if any transformation to y would help my models \(R^2\). From the above graph we can see that either a \(\log(Y)\) or a \(\sqrt{\sqrt{Y}}\) may benefit the model. After trying both, the \(\sqrt{\sqrt{Y}}\) transformation gives us the best \(R^2\) but the validation \(R^2\) goes down significantly. However, the log transformation gave me both a good \(R^2\) and validation \(R^2\).

I also decided to graph each of the variables that had similar x axis limits to visually show their correlation. In this plot we can see GrLivArea, TotalBsmtSF, and X1stFlrSF have pretty similar slope. I decided to try interacting each one with another in my lm and when I added TotalBsmtSF:GrLivArea + GrLivArea:X1stFlrSF it made my \(R^2\) higher!

plot_data <- mytrain %>%
  dplyr::select(SalePrice, GarageCars, OverallQual) %>%
  tidyr::pivot_longer(cols = -SalePrice, names_to = "Variable", values_to = "Value")

ggplot(plot_data, aes(x = Value, y = log(SalePrice), color = Variable)) +
  geom_point(alpha = 0.5) +
  geom_smooth(method = "lm",formula = y~x, se = FALSE) +  
  facet_wrap(~Variable, scales = "free_x") +

       x = "Predictor Value",
       y = "log(SalePrice)") +
  theme_minimal()

From the plots above I tried the interaction between Garage Cars and Overall Qual. I found that the result wasnt significant and so I didnt keep it. As seen above, their graphs are pretty different and it looks like they are not very meaninful together so I wasnt surprised when their interaction wasnt significant.


I also tried interacting a few other variables I guessed would be correlated and found that as.factor(Neighborhood):OverallQual also helped my models \(R^2\).




Final lm

In conclusion Box-Cox, graphing, and guessing based on the pairs plot were the three methods I used to find all the terms in my final lm: \[ \begin{equation} \log(\text{SalePrice}) = \beta_0 + \beta_1 \cdot \text{GrLivArea} + \beta_2 \cdot \text{KitchenQual} + \beta_3 \cdot \text{GarageCars} + \beta_4 \cdot \text{TotalBsmtSF} + \beta_{5i} \cdot \text{Neighborhood}_i + \beta_6 \cdot \text{OverallQual} +\\ \beta_7 \cdot \text{X1stFlrSF} + \beta_8 \cdot \text{YearBuilt} + \beta_9 \cdot (\text{TotalBsmtSF} \times \text{GrLivArea}) + \beta_{10} \cdot (\text{GrLivArea} \times \text{X1stFlrSF}) + \epsilon \end{equation} \]


Final R-Squareds and Validation R-Squareds

yht <- predict(lm, newdata= mytest)
yht <- na.omit(yht)
  # Compute y-bar
ybar <- mean(log(mytest$SalePrice)) 

  # Compute SSTO
SSTO <- sum( (log(mytest$SalePrice) - ybar)^2 )
  
  # Compute SSE for each model using y - yhat
SSEl <- sum( (log(mytest$SalePrice) - yht)^2 )
  
  # Compute R-squared for each
rsl <-  1-(SSEl/SSTO)
  
  # Compute adjusted R-squared for each
n <- length(mytest$SalePrice) #sample size
pl <- length(coef(mytrain))
rstal<- 1-(n-1)/(n-pl)*SSEl/SSTO 
  
my_output_table2 <- data.frame(Model = c("True"), `Original R2` = c(summary(lm)$r.squared), `Orig. Adj. R-squared` = c(summary(lm)$adj.r.squared), `Validation R-squared` = c(rsl), `Validation Adj. R^2` = c(rstal))

colnames(my_output_table2) <- c("Model", "Original $R^2$", "Original Adj. $R^2$", "Validation $R^2$", "Validation Adj. $R^2$")

Graphing my Final lm:

b<-coef(lm)
library(ggplot2)

ggplot(mytrain, aes(x = GrLivArea, y = SalePrice)) +
  geom_point(alpha = 0.5, color = "#af8382") +
  
  stat_function(fun = function(GrLivArea) {
    KitchenQualTA = 1
    GarageCars = 2
    TotalBsmtSF = 750
    NeighborhoodNAmes = 1
    X1stFlrSF = 1000
    YearBuilt = 2006
    OverallQual = 5
    
    exp(b[1] + 
        b[2]*GrLivArea + 
        b[3]*KitchenQualTA + 
        b[6]*GarageCars + 
        b[7]*TotalBsmtSF + 
        b[19]*NeighborhoodNAmes + 
        b[32]*X1stFlrSF + 
        b[33]*YearBuilt + 
        b[46]*NeighborhoodNAmes*OverallQual + 
        b[59]*GrLivArea*TotalBsmtSF + 
        b[60]*GrLivArea*X1stFlrSF)
  }, color = "#746770", size = 0.8) +
  
  labs(title = "Stat Function Plot Based on Model Coefficients",
       x = "GrLivArea",
       y = "Predicted SalePrice") +
  
  scale_y_continuous(labels = scales::comma) +  
  scale_x_continuous(labels = scales::comma) +
  
  theme_minimal()

This graph shows the relationship between GrLivArea and SalePrice using actual data points and predicted values from my linear model. The curve shows how the model expects sale prices to change as GrLivArea increases.
